### 3. Impulse Response Functions

We use recursive (Cholesky) identification with EPU ordered first, meaning EPU shocks can affect all variables on impact, but no other shock moves EPU contemporaneously.

**PAYEMS:** Employment falls in response to an EPU shock, but relatively slowly. The trough is around month 4--5 at roughly -0.013 percentage points, and the effect is significant from months 2 to 12. The slow adjustment reflects the costs of changing workforce size -- firms are reluctant to cut jobs quickly even when uncertainty rises.

![Impulse response of month-on-month employment growth (PAYEMS) to a one-unit structural EPU shock, from the recursive VAR(1) with EPU ordered first. Solid line: point estimate. Dashed lines: 95% bootstrap confidence bands (100 replications). Horizontal axis: months after the shock (0--24). Vertical axis: response in percentage points. Estimated on 1985M2--2019M12.](output/irf_payems.png){width=65%}

**INDPRO:** Industrial production reacts faster and more sharply, dropping immediately and bottoming out around month 3--4 at roughly -0.05 percentage points. The effect is significant from months 2 to 10 and fades by around month 20. Firms can cut output more easily than they can let workers go.

![Impulse response of month-on-month industrial production growth (INDPRO) to a one-unit structural EPU shock, from the recursive VAR(1) with EPU ordered first. Solid line: point estimate. Dashed lines: 95% bootstrap confidence bands (100 replications). Horizontal axis: months after the shock (0--24). Vertical axis: response in percentage points. Estimated on 1985M2--2019M12.](output/irf_indpro.png){width=65%}

Both responses are consistent with the standard uncertainty channel: higher policy uncertainty leads firms to cut production and delay hiring.

